/*
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    Custom overrides for nf-core/funcscan
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    1. Pin pyhmmer<0.12 for GECCO and DeepBGC to fix:
           AttributeError: 'str' object has no attribute 'decode'
       (pyhmmer >=0.12 changed hmm.accession from bytes to str)
    2. Resource caps for DTU HPC — 20-core / 128 GB nodes.
       funcscan's base.config has no ceiling guard — retries scale CPUs/memory
       unboundedly and exceed node limits. Hard-coded values aligned with bacass's
       heaviest processes, which are proven to fit DTU HPC.
    3. DeepBGC publishDir fix: ext.prefix="deepbgc" (static) causes all samples to
       publish to the same path → results overwrite. publishDir override adds meta.id
       to the path and renames data files from "deepbgc.*" to "<sample_id>.*".
    4. COMBGC Sample_ID fix: comBGC.py derives sample from filename, yielding "deepbgc"
       (DeepBGC) and "<sample_id>_gecco" (GECCO) instead of the actual sample ID. Fix:
       pass --sample-id <meta.id> via ext.args (requires comBGC.py and combgc.nf patches).
    5. GECCO publishDir fix: ext.prefix="${meta.id}_gecco" adds "_gecco" to all output
       filenames. publishDir override strips the "_gecco" infix from the prefix portion so
       published files have clean per-sample names: bgc/gecco/<id>/<id>.clusters.tsv, etc.
    6. DeepBGC performance fix (same pattern as 7 below): funcscan allocates 1 CPU to DEEPBGC_PIPELINE. HMMER's
       hmmscan auto-detects available CPUs — with 1 allocated, it runs single-threaded,
       taking 3–5h per contig. Assemblies with 80+ contigs exceed the 24h wall time.
       Fix: allocate 5 CPUs and run on local scratch. Measured Mar 2026 (bstat + bpeek):
       - HMMER uses ~5 effective CPUs regardless of whether 10 are allocated (NFS I/O bound
         on the 2.8 GB Pfam DB, which is accessed via symlink even with scratch=true).
       - Observed: 39m35s for 339-CDS contig, 35m53s for 301-CDS contig (≈5 CPUs effective).
       - DTU HPC hpc_default_slot_limit = 284 slots. At cpus=10: only 28 concurrent jobs.
         At cpus=5: 56 concurrent jobs — 2× throughput with no per-job performance loss.
       - Peak memory: 280–400 MB across all jobs (HMMER streams Pfam DB, does not cache it).
         4 GB gives 10× headroom. 16 GB was 40× over-allocated.
       Resources are fixed (not scaled by attempt): failures are node-specific conda
       activation errors, not OOM/timeout — retries escape the bad node, not add resources.
       maxRetries = 10 to tolerate repeated bad-node draws.
    7. DeepARG performance fix: same pattern — 1 CPU / 2 GB with a 4.8 GB diamond database.
       Fix: 8 CPUs / 8 GB / scratch = true (diamond reads DB from local disk).
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
*/

// BACASS_DIR is exported by setup.sh, available at runtime
def bacassDir = System.getenv('BACASS_DIR') ?: '/work3/josne/github/bacass'

process {
    // ── pyhmmer<0.12 fixes ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    withName: 'GECCO_RUN' {
        conda = "${bacassDir}/conf/gecco_environment.yml"
        // GECCO module's mv loop fails with "same file" when input.baseName == prefix
        // (i.e. when meta.id matches the assembly basename, which is always the case here).
        // errorStrategy = 'ignore' was tried but drops the output channel — results never
        // get published. Fix: set ext.prefix to a different value so mv succeeds and NF
        // collects outputs normally. The suffix is cosmetic; downstream COMBGC uses meta.id.
        ext.prefix = { "${meta.id}_gecco" }
        // Fix publishDir: ext.prefix adds "_gecco" suffix to all output filenames, e.g.:
        //   S0204_gecco.clusters.tsv, S0204_gecco.genes.tsv, S0204_gecco_cluster_1.gbk
        // Strip the "_gecco" infix from the prefix portion so published files have clean names:
        //   bgc/gecco/S0204/S0204.clusters.tsv, bgc/gecco/S0204/S0204_cluster_1.gbk, etc.
        // replaceFirst targets "^<meta.id>_gecco" (the prefix), preserving the rest of the
        // filename unchanged — handles both dot-separated files and _cluster_N GBK files.
        publishDir = [
            path: { "${params.outdir}/bgc/gecco/${meta.id}" },
            mode: 'copy',
            saveAs: { filename ->
                if (filename.equals('versions.yml')) return null
                filename.replaceFirst("^${meta.id}_gecco", "${meta.id}")
            },
        ]
    }
    withName: 'DEEPBGC_PIPELINE' {
        conda         = "${bacassDir}/conf/deepbgc_environment.yml"
        errorStrategy = 'retry'
        maxRetries    = 10
        scratch       = true
        cpus          = 5
        memory        = 4.GB
        time          = 48.h
        // DeepBGC mv collision analysis:
        //   The module script does two mv steps:
        //     1. mv "${genome.baseName}/" "${prefix}/"   (dir rename)
        //     2. for i in $(find -name '${genome.baseName}*' -type f); do
        //            mv $i ${i/${genome.baseName}/${prefix}}
        //        done
        //   Default (prefix == meta.id == "S0679", genome.baseName == "S0679"):
        //     Step 1: skipped (same name — bash condition false).
        //     Step 2: ${i/S0679/S0679} = rename-to-self → bash -e exits with error.
        //   Fix: use a static prefix that shares no substring with any sample ID.
        //     "deepbgc" never appears in any sample ID (S0679, S0344, etc.), so:
        //     Step 1: mv S0679/ deepbgc/  ✓
        //     Step 2: ${i/S0679/deepbgc} where i = ./deepbgc/S0679.bgc.tsv
        //             → ./deepbgc/deepbgc.bgc.tsv  ✓  (substitution only hits filename)
        //     Module output: ${prefix}/${prefix}.bgc.tsv = deepbgc/deepbgc.bgc.tsv  ✓
        //     COMBGC receives the bgc_tsv channel entry and runs with all three tools.
        //   Why ${meta.id}_deepbgc fails: after dir rename to S0679_deepbgc/,
        //     ${i/S0679/S0679_deepbgc} where i = ./S0679_deepbgc/S0679.bgc.tsv
        //     → the substitution hits the directory portion first → ./S0679_deepbgc_deepbgc/... ✗
        ext.prefix = "deepbgc"
        // Fix publishDir: all samples share prefix="deepbgc" → all publish to the same path
        // → results overwrite each other. Override to put each sample in its own subdirectory
        // and rename the data files (deepbgc.*) to use the sample ID (meta.id.*).
        // saveAs strips the "deepbgc/" subdir and renames "deepbgc.<ext>" → "<meta.id>.<ext>".
        // evaluation/ plots are renamed deepbgc.*.png → <id>.*.png; LOG.txt and README.txt are unchanged.
        publishDir = [
            path: { "${params.outdir}/bgc/deepbgc/${meta.id}" },
            mode: 'copy',
            saveAs: { filename ->
                if (filename.equals('versions.yml')) return null
                def inner = filename.replaceFirst('^deepbgc/', '')
                // Rename top-level data files: deepbgc.bgc.tsv → <id>.bgc.tsv
                inner = inner.replaceFirst('^deepbgc\\.', "${meta.id}.")
                // Rename evaluation plots: evaluation/deepbgc.bgc.png → evaluation/<id>.bgc.png
                inner.replaceFirst('/deepbgc\\.', "/${meta.id}.")
            },
        ]
    }
    withName: 'COMBGC' {
        // comBGC.py derives Sample_ID from the input filename. With our ext.prefix overrides:
        //   DeepBGC → file is "deepbgc.bgc.tsv"       → Sample_ID = "deepbgc"   (wrong)
        //   GECCO   → file is "S0204_gecco.clusters.tsv" → Sample_ID = "S0204_gecco" (wrong)
        // Fix: pass --sample-id <meta.id> to comBGC.py so it uses the correct sample identifier.
        // Requires comBGC.py patch (--sample-id arg added) and combgc.nf patch ($args wired in).
        ext.args = { "--sample-id ${meta.id}" }
    }
    withName: 'AMPCOMBI2_COMPLETE' {
        // ampcombi complete requires >=2 summary files but single-sample runs only produce 1.
        // This is a summarization step — safe to ignore for single-sample runs.
        errorStrategy = 'ignore'
    }

    // ── DTU HPC resource caps ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
    // Reference ceiling from bacass (proven on cluster): 20 CPUs / 120 GB max.

    // process_high: funcscan default → 12*attempt CPUs / 72.GB*attempt memory.
    //   attempt 2 uncapped: 24 CPU / 144 GB  ✗  (no 20-core / 128 GB node can host this)
    //   after fix:          12 CPU (fixed) / 60.GB*attempt → 60 / 120 GB  ✓
    withLabel: 'process_high' {
        cpus   = 12
        memory = { 60.GB * task.attempt }
        time   = { 16.h * task.attempt }
    }

    // process_high_memory: funcscan default → 200.GB*attempt.
    //   attempt 1 uncapped: 200 GB  ✗  (exceeds all 128 GB nodes)
    //   after fix:          120 GB (fixed, matches bacass hard ceiling)  ✓
    withLabel: 'process_high_memory' {
        memory = 120.GB
    }

    // AMPCOMBI2_PARSETABLES: funcscan default → 16*attempt CPUs.
    //   attempt 2 uncapped: 32 CPUs  ✗  (no node has 32 cores)
    //   after fix:          16 CPUs (fixed)  ✓
    withName: 'AMPCOMBI2_PARSETABLES' {
        cpus = 16
    }

    // DEEPARG_PREDICT: funcscan default → 1 CPU / 2.GB*attempt.
    //   DeepARG uses diamond (BLAST) against a 4.8 GB database — I/O-heavy and multi-threaded.
    //   With 1 CPU, diamond runs single-threaded; 2 GB is also too tight for the DB + overhead.
    //   Same fix as DEEPBGC: fixed resources + scratch so diamond reads the DB from local disk.
    //   8 CPUs = 2 tasks per 20-core node with 4 spare for other processes.
    //   Resources fixed (not scaled): failures are node/conda issues, not resource exhaustion.
    withName: 'DEEPARG_PREDICT' {
        scratch        = true
        cpus           = 8
        memory         = 8.GB
        time           = 4.h
        // Retry on exit code 1 (NFS read failures: Theano JIT headers, .so loading).
        // Resources are fixed — failures are node-specific NFS issues, not OOM.
        errorStrategy  = { task.exitStatus in [1, 130, 131, 137, 139, 140, 143, 104, 175] ? 'retry' : 'finish' }
        maxRetries     = 5
    }

    // ANTISMASH_ANTISMASH: funcscan default → 8*attempt CPUs / 64.GB*attempt memory.
    //   attempt 2 uncapped: 16 CPU / 128 GB — fits but leaves no OS headroom
    //   after fix:          8 CPU (fixed) / 60.GB*attempt → 60 / 120 GB  ✓
    withName: 'ANTISMASH_ANTISMASH' {
        cpus   = 8
        memory = { 60.GB * task.attempt }
        time   = { 12.h * task.attempt }
    }

    // BAKTA_BAKTA: same ceiling issue as ANTISMASH. Skipped when pre-annotated input
    // is provided (our default), but capped defensively.
    //   attempt 2 uncapped: 16 CPU / 128 GB — no OS headroom
    //   after fix:          8 CPU (fixed) / 60.GB*attempt → 60 / 120 GB  ✓
    withName: 'BAKTA_BAKTA' {
        cpus   = 8
        memory = { 60.GB * task.attempt }
        time   = { 8.h * task.attempt }
    }
}
